                                <p> LAUSANNE, Switzerland, Sept 23 (Reuters) - The prize money  in men's doubles tournaments looks set to be reduced next year,  the ATP chief executive officer Mark Miles said on Monday.</p>
                                <p> Speaking at the World Sports Forum held at the Olympic  Museum in Lausanne, Miles said that an announcement to explain  some 'scaling back in the compensation for doubles' was due to  be made very soon.</p>
                                <p> "It's a reallocation of the prize-money really. It will mean  a few changes. But it will not be something done to put doubles  out of business," Miles told Reuters.</p>
                                <p> He explained that prize money at events on the ATP Tour this  year had been distributed 75 percent to singles and 25 percent  to doubles and that this arrangement will change in 2003.</p>
                                <p> He declined to say what the new distribution would be, but  did not deny a suggestion that it could be 80-20.</p>
                                <p> He said that the changes would be made in a bid to ease the  pressure on tournaments and their promoters in the current  difficult financial climate.</p>
                                <p> "This will ease things a bit for everyone and it will not  threaten doubles," he said. "It is something we will be saying  more about in the next few weeks - certainly before next  January."</p>
